@node "Overview" "Overview"

  Introduction.

   CoolIO is a little commodity (< than 20Kb) that patches some
   system functions, and allows some pre-selected tasks that only load
   IFF-ILBM picture to load virtually any file-format. But moreover
   it can also modify any saving process, in order to modify a saved
   file.

   But as all this may seem quite meaningless, look at this example
   explaining how CoolIO works. Imagine you are under DeluxePaint. Well,
   this paint-program only accepts IFF-ILBMS. Launch the @{"CoolIOPrefs" link "Configuration" 0}
   program, and select the "DPaint" task as a client for the loading
   patcher. Now, DPaint loads GIF, JPEG, PNG, PCX, etc. as long as you
   have those datatypes in your system.

   Imagine now, you would like a program that automagically turns your
   picture created by Imagine or LightWave into JPEG or anything else.
   Go to the CoolIOPrefs, select your program's task as a client for
   the saving patch, select a program that will convert your picture
   into jpeg, just put the good parameters, select any prefix you
   want to distinguish the to-be-converted pictures, and that's all.

   Of course, the loading patch @{"needs" link "Requirements" 0} at least the AmigaOS3.0 or
   higher to work properly. You can use the saving patch with
   AmigaOS2.0 or higher.

   This program has been successfully tested and retested by many
   people, however this is still a PATCH, so you use it at your own
   risks. The author is NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR ANY LOSS OF DATA THAT
   COULD OCCUR WHILE THE PROGRAM IS RUNNING. If you are not sure of
   what your are doing, please stop it, and put the program into the
   trashcan.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

  Installation.

   The current package needs no assign, so you can drag the drawer
   anywhere on your harddisk. This is so simple that you should not
   need an installation script - hope so.

   In the CoolIO drawer, you will mainly find those files:
     - CoolIO, the main program
     - CoolIOPrefs, to modify the preferences
     - Docs, the documentation directory

   CoolIO is a commodity, so, putting it in the WBStartup directory of
   your amiga isn't a bad idea. CoolIOPrefs can be kept anywhere, in
   the CoolIO directory, or in the Prefs one.

   If you need a localization, you can put the catalog drawer in your
   LOCALE: directory. Only the french catalog is currently
   available. If you translate it into your language, please send me
   that file (yes, I offer a FREE KEYFILE(°)... :-))
   However, all this is quite simple, and you should read any text
   from CoolIO.



(°) Yes, it's a joke. Guess why... :-)
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

   What you basically need to run CoolIO is an amiga (well, you
   guessed), AmigaOS 2.0 or higher, and 20Kb free.

   However, the loading patch really needs AmigaOS 3.0 or higher,
   because it uses the datatypes.library to convert the alien
   fileformat into IFF-ILBM. So, if you only have a 2.x OS, you won't
   be able to use all the features CoolIO offers. Sorry.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"

   The CoolIOPrefs program will help you to configure CoolIO. Please
   pay attention, that's not always an easy job, as you will have to
   explore the task list, and choose your task.

   Not all tasks work well with CoolIO. While most programs should
   be OK for CoolIO, some may do some unexpected things such as:

    - The task opens and closes the file many times when loading or
   saving. Yes, it does exist ! If it happens while loading, no real
   trouble but it may result in hours of computation for a single file
   (at this time, CoolIO does not remember if a file has been opened
   before). If it happens while saving, you will lose your file.

   - The task does not use the DOS to access the file. Well, who wants
   to use CoolIO with its MegaDemo ? :-)


   The task name CoolIO uses is nothing more than the filename
   without the path. So, the task name of the sys:paint/UglyPainter
   will be uglyPainter (CoolIO is not case-sensitive for the task
   names).

  The CoolIOPrefs program.
  ------------------------

   Two groups are available in the CoolIOPrefs window, one to select
   the tasks that will be patched when @{"loading" link "LoadingPatch" 0}, and one for the tasks
   patched when @{"saving" link "SavingPatch" 0}.

   CoolIO uses notification to detect if its preferences file has been
   modified. So, you don't need to quit and re-run CoolIO to take the
   modifications into account.
@endnode

@node "LoadingPatch" "The loading patch"

   In the LOADING TASK clients' group, you will have to select the
   tasks that CoolIO should patch.

   There are actually two useful gadgets : Add task, and Del (which
   stands for "delete").

   Use the "Add task" button to pop up the task list onto the screen,
   and select the task. Of course, if the program you want to
   patch is NOT running, you will not see its name in the list !
   Just select a name, and push "Select" to add it to the list, or
   "Cancel" to forget it.

   To delete a task name, select it in the list gadget, and click on
   the "Del" gadget. Remember, if you had made an error, you can
   select either the "Restore" or "Last Saved" option in the menu.



   The EASIEST way to choose a program is to launch it, and select it
   in the list.



   Here are some programs that have been tested to work well with
   CoolIO at loading.

   DeluxePaint IV, V
   LightWave
   AdPro v2.5 (Taskname: IFF, and select the IFF Loader).
   CineMorph Jr

   etc, the list is NOT complete.
   If there are more, please let me know !

@endnode

@node "SavingPatch" "The saving patch"

   You can configure the saving patch like the loading one, with one
   exception: Once you have choosen the task name, another window
   appears, where you must configure some parameters.

   First, you must choose a command that will convert your file. If
   you need to convert graphic fileformats, you should get somewhere
   (ie. on Aminet) some converter that accepts arguments on the
   command line (GfxConv does that, AFAIK, or watch at the PBM
   package).
   So, you should put the name of your converter into  the string
   gadget, with the correct parameters. You must put the parameters
   in the following form : c:MyConverter "%s" "%d".

   %s is for the sourcefile (with the prefix)
   %d is the destination file (without the prefix).

   Of course, you can choose an AmigaDos script instead of a program.
   Just set the "script" flag on the file, or call the command
   <<EXECUTE myscript "%s" "%d">>. There are some example script in
   the directory Scripts/.

   Then you must pick up a prefix for your command line. When CoolIO
   will see the selected task saving a file with a name beginning with
   this prefix, it will patch it and call your converter.

   ie. imagine your prefix is "_COOL_". If you save a file as
   "sys:pictures/mypic.iff", nothing will happen, as the selected
   prefix does not appear.
   At the contrary, if I save this file as
   "sys:pictures/_COOL_mypic.jpg", then CoolIo will see the prefix and
   call the converter.

   In such a case, the given "%s" source file will be
   "sys:pictures/_COOL_mypic.jpg", and the destination file "%d" will
   be "sys:pictures/mypic.jpg".

   !! BEWARE !! "sys:picture/my_COOL_pic.jpg" is DEFINITIVELY NOT a
   valid filename if you wish to call the converter. Look in the
   dictionnary what a prefix is, if you don't know what it means.

   Here is a list of programs that have been successfully tested, but
   nearly all programs should accept the CoolIO saving patch.

   DeluxePaint
   Cinemorph Jr
   GoldEd
   Brillance
   LighWave
   Imagine

   If there are more, please let me know !

@endnode

@node "Problems" "Problems"

   Problems ? WHAT problems ?

   No, there should not have any problem with CoolIO running at the
   background, as it does nearly nothing with non-clients task, and
   don't disturb them.

   Of course, you should TEST CoolIO with every client task to verify
   that they are compatible. If it works, then keep it, else delete
   the task name from the client-list.


   HOWEVER : There may have problems with oldish datatypes that
   incorrectly support the write method of the library. Many problems
   have occurred to me and to my beta-testers, such as:
    - Some (currently a JPEG) datatype don't transmit the palette to
   the datatype. The result is a dark picture when loading.
   - Some (currently GIF) datatype don't transmit the correct page
   width/height for the picture. Not a big problem, though, just a
   message in DPaint saying that it is loading a 0x0x256 cols picture.

   ALL this problems are only due to the datatypes, and can easily be
   fixed by replacing the datatype with a newer one (now everything
   works great on my amiga).
@endnode

